issue.title: Extend compatibility for Zucchetti ZCS HYD6000-ZP1
issue.body:
### Is your feature request related to a problem?

I am currently using the ha-solarman integration with a Zucchetti ZCS HYD6000-ZP1 inverter. I've noticed that when using the sofar_g3.yaml configuration (which seems to be the closest available option), not all entities related to the inverter are being detected correctly. This limits the full visibility and control of my solar PV system within Home Assistant.

### Describe the solution you'd like

I would like to request an extension of this integration's compatibility to include the Zucchetti ZCS HYD6000-ZP1 inverter model. The goal is to ensure that all relevant entities are properly exposed in Home Assistant.

### Describe alternatives you've considered

I have attempted to use the existing sofar_g3.yaml configuration as it appeared to be the closest match, but as described, it does not provide full coverage for my inverter's data. I have not yet explored deep reverse engineering of the Modbus protocol myself, hoping for a more guided approach or an official integration path.

### How can I contribute?
I am keen to actively contribute to help extend this compatibility. Could you kindly provide guidance on how I can best assist? For example:

- What additional information would be most helpful from my side? (e.g., specific datalogger logs, raw Modbus register dumps if I can obtain them, detailed technical documentation of the Solarman protocol or Modbus registers for the Zucchetti ZCS HYD6000-ZP1 inverter, etc.)
- Is there a preferred methodology for mapping new inverters within this project? (e.g., is there a specific process for identifying Modbus registers, or a template for new inverter configuration files?)
- What is the recommended process for proposing changes or adding new configuration files once I have gathered more data or made progress?

I am available to provide any further details, run specific tests, and to test new implementations or configurations once they are available.

Built a House Price Prediction ML model using Python & Scikit-learn.
Focused on data preprocessing, feature encoding, and Linear Regression to predict prices accurately.

Fix LazyBooleanExpression links

These links were using the wrong name (_LazyBooleanOperatorExpression_)
which doesn't exist.

Fix MetaListPaths link

This was missing an `s` as a plural.

Remove unneeded grammar links

Now that mdbook-spec auto-generates link definitions for grammar names,
there's no need to be explicit about these.

Fix recursive root-accessible grammar check

This fixes a bug in how the `@root` grammar validation was done. It was
not properly handling recursive rules because when walking the tree it
would find itself, and thus mark it as "used". What we really want is to
only walk starting from the root set, and don't remove recursive
definitions from the root set.

Convert remaining grammar rule references to links

In https://github.com/rust-lang/reference/pull/1787 I missed linkify-ing
references to grammar rules that weren't links. This makes sure that
they are linked and validated.

Align pattern destructuring with rest of doc

Previously, `patterns.destructure.placeholder` referred to the `_` in a
destructuring pattern as "placeholder" and `..` as "wildcard". This
directly contradicted the definition of struct patterns and tuple
(struct) patterns, which (indirectly) define `_` as a wildcard pattern
and `..` as a structure pattern et cetera (for structs, enums, and union
values) or rest pattern (for tuples, tuple structs, slices, and arrays).

Update the paragraph to use "wildcard pattern", "et cetera", and "rest
pattern" instead.  Moreover, add links to their respective
sections/statements. Finally, update the rule name to
`r[patterns.destructure.wildcard]`.

Use extern "system" instead of "stdcall" in example

`stdcall` is only correct for 32-bit Windows and may be a hard error on other platforms in the future. Whereas `system` is correct for all Windows targets.

pull_request.title: feat: add migration state persistence and resume functionality for large-scale migrations
pull_request.body:
## Summary
Implements comprehensive migration state persistence and resume functionality for the `env-migrate` command to handle large-scale migrations with 450+ sites that may experience failures and timeouts.

## Features Implemented
- **Migration State Management**: Persistent JSON-based state tracking with site-level progress
- **Resume Functionality**: Resume incomplete migrations from checkpoints with `--resume <migration-id>`
- **Selective Retry**: Skip failed (`--skip-failed`) or timeout (`--skip-timeouts`) sites, or retry only failed sites (`--retry-failed`)
- **Migration Management**: List incomplete migrations with `--list-migrations`
- **Lock File System**: Prevent concurrent migrations with process-level locking
- **Enhanced Logging**: Comprehensive logs and migration summaries in timestamped directories

## Key Benefits
- **Fault Tolerance**: Survive crashes, network issues, and system reboots
- **Time Savings**: Resume from checkpoint instead of restarting 450+ site migrations
- **Selective Control**: Target only problematic sites while preserving successful work
- **Progress Visibility**: Clear status tracking and audit trail
- **Production Ready**: Handle large-scale migrations reliably

## Usage Examples
```bash
# List incomplete migrations
wfuwp env-migrate --list-migrations

# Resume a failed migration
wfuwp env-migrate --resume env-migrate-2025-08-17T12-34-56-abc123

# Skip previously failed sites
wfuwp env-migrate --resume <migration-id> --skip-failed

# Retry only failed sites
wfuwp env-migrate --resume <migration-id> --retry-failed
```

## Test Plan
- ‚úÖ Command interface accepts all new options
- ‚úÖ `--list-migrations` displays empty state correctly
- ‚úÖ Help output shows all new options
- ‚úÖ Backward compatibility maintained for existing workflows
- ‚úÖ TypeScript compilation successful
- üîÑ Next: Test with actual migration scenarios to validate state persistence

## Technical Implementation
- **Non-intrusive**: Existing migration workflow unchanged
- **Modular**: State management isolated in `src/utils/migration-state.ts`
- **Backward Compatible**: All existing commands continue to work
- **Hybrid Architecture**: Layers new functionality without breaking changes

This enhancement transforms `env-migrate` from an "all-or-nothing" operation into a robust, resumable process suitable for production migrations with hundreds of sites.

release.name: 2.0 Update
release.body:
This update adds ability scores, a new menu system, many new species traits, and more.

## New Features
### Menu System
- Accessed via `/function dnd:menu`
- Has 4 pages: Species, Cheats, Links, and Admin.
- Species page
  - Shows a list of all available species
  - Traits are shown in hover text
  - Some species (like elves and dwarves) have subpages for their subspecies.
  - Clicking on a species activates it.
    - This unfortunately gives a popup warning about the command, but you can ignore that.
- Cheats page
  - Shows 2 buttons for each cheat: Enable and Disable
- Links page
  - Shows various links to stuff about the pack
- Admin page
  - Only available to players with the `developer` tag.
  - Has several useful utilities which make debugging easier.
  - If you're planning on modifying this pack, or just want the neat utilities, run `/tag @s developer`, and it'll show up on the menu.
### Ability Scores
- There are 6 scores: Strength (STR), Dexterity (DEX), Constitution (CON), Intelligence (INT), Wisdom (WIS), and Charisma (CHA).
- Each score boosts certain traits.
  - STR boosts attack damage and attack knockback.
  - DEX boosts speed and agility.
  - CON boosts health and resistance to damage.
  - INT, WIS, and CHA currently don't boost anything, and this is due to a couple reasons.
    - Not really anything to boost. There aren't really any mental traits in Minecraft.
    - The few things I thought of would be very difficult to implement.
    - I plan to give these three scores uses in future updates, but for now they're useless.
- None of the boosts are insane, but they're minor little tweaks that you'll notice here and there.
- Each species gives a bonus to an ability score.
### New Species Traits
- Many new bonuses across nearly every species.
- Hill Dwarf
  - Extra heart
- Wood Elf
  - Turns invisible while sneaking in 2-block tall plants (tall grass, rose bush, sugarcane, etc).
- Aarakocra
  - Higher damage (Claws)
- Earth Genasi
  - Higher movement efficiency (like in soul sand)
- Goliath
  - Natural armor
- Bugbear
  - Longer attack/entity interact reach
- Shifter
  - Night vision
- Centaur
  - Higher damage (Hooves)
- Minotaur
  - Much higher damage (Horns)
- Satyr
  - Extra damage (Horns)
- Tortle
  - Extra damage (Claws)
    - Wait tortoises have claws???
  - Much longer breath
- Lizardfolk
  - Higher damage (Bite)
  - Natural armor (Only while not wearing armor)
- Aasimar
  - Healing Hands (Ability)
    - Heals nearby entity
    - Can be used once per day
- Firbolg
  - Temporary Invisibility
    - Turns you invisible for 10 seconds
    - Can be used once per day
- Eladrin
  - Can teleport like Shadar-Kai
- Kobold
  - Now gets periodic darkness effect like Dark Elves.
- Tabaxi
  - Higher damage (Claws)
  - Short speed boosts
    - Lasts for 10 seconds, recharges after 30 seconds
- Orc
  - Long speed boosts
    - Lasts for 60 seconds, can be used once a day
### Abilities Menu
- Access by pressing G (by default, differs if you've changed your quick options keybind)
- Lists all abilities
  - Not all are allowed to be used by your current species, but I am *not* going to create 300+ (once I add more abilities with like classes and stuff) just to display all the abilities your species can personally use.

### Wildhunt Shifter
- Has two different effects while shifted, depending on if other players are online.
- If in singleplayer, all nearby mobs have the glowing effect.
- If in multiplayer, all nearby mobs have a particle effect only visible to currently shifted Wildshape Shifters.
### Human
- Nothing interesting about them
## Changes
- Gnomes have been split into Forest and Rock Gnomes
  - This is so the new ability scores can differ across them.
- Githyanki and Githzerai are now under a Gith main species
  - This is so an ability score can match between them
    - Note: Githzerai suck, use Githyanki
- Eladrin are now properly in the elf species
  - Somehow I missed that.
- Teleporting is now an ability
  - You can activate the ability to get the ender pearl
  - It'll disappear after 10 seconds
  - If another player holds it, it'll also disappear.
    - This is one of a few anti-exploiting measures I've added when it comes to the teleporting ability.
- Messages put into chat (like "Unshifting...") now use `tellraw` instead of `say`
  - This prevents it from being visible to all players.
- Moved old menu system to `/function dnd:system/classic_menu`
  - This won't be updated much in the future, but I'm leaving it in the pack because I spent too much time on it to just delete it.
- Cheats are no longer reset upon world load/pack reload.
  - There are also separate commands for disabling/enabling cheats.
- Weapon proficiencies now increase attack speed instead of attack damage.
  - This just makes more sense.
- There are generally a few more messages that'll be put into chat to make debugging easier, and give more feedback for the user.

## Technical Changes
### Popup Title
- Popup title has been delayed a tiny bit, which hopefully should make it always appear to players without a species.
- The command for the popup title is now `/function dnd:system/popuptitle`, which is more accurate.
### Speed changes to counteract MC-195830
- Higher Speed is now set using a modifier, as modifiers aren't reset on world load.
- Lower speed is now set using a tagging system, so species with a lower speed will always have their speed set after world load, even if it's reset.
### Performance Optimizations
- Several reused targeters in the tick file have been moved to subfiles to reduce [forking](https://datapack.wiki/wiki/command/execute#forking).
- It's nothing major, but should significantly boost performance in big servers.
### Misc Technical Changes
- Added new crouch detection system.

## Bug Fixes
- Fixed speed being reset on world load.
  - This isn't a bug with my datapack, and it's actually a bug with Minecraft (MC-195830), but I still wanted to fix it, so I found a way to counteract it.

## Greptile Summary

This PR adds support for boolean data types in the `list.max()` and `list.min()` functions, addressing issue #4914. Previously, these functions only accepted numeric types and would throw a TypeError when applied to lists of boolean values.

The changes involve updating type validation logic in two core Rust files:
- `src/daft-functions-list/src/max.rs`: Modified the `get_return_field()` function to accept boolean types alongside numeric types
- `src/daft-functions-list/src/min.rs`: Applied the same type validation update for consistency

The implementation leverages existing aggregation infrastructure that already supports boolean comparisons (where False < True in natural ordering). The change only required updating the schema validation from `field.dtype.is_numeric()` to `field.dtype.is_numeric() || field.dtype.is_boolean()` in both functions.

Comprehensive test coverage was added in `tests/recordbatch/list/test_list_bool_aggs.py`, verifying correct behavior across various scenarios including all-True/all-False lists, mixed boolean values, null handling, and both variable-length and fixed-size list types. The tests confirm that boolean semantics are properly implemented (True > False) and that null handling follows standard SQL conventions.

This enhancement provides consistency with other boolean aggregation functions already available in the codebase (like `list_bool_and` and `list_bool_or`) and aligns with user expectations for min/max operations on boolean data.
